    "text": "Absolutely — here’s a **clean IRS-cited deadline table** for common **U.S. federal small-business filing deadlines**.\n\n## U.S. Federal Small-Business Tax Deadlines\n\n| Business type | Typical federal return | Deadline for calendar-year taxpayers | Notes |\n|---|---|---:|---|\n| Sole proprietor | **Form 1040 + Schedule C** | **April 15** | Includes most single-member LLCs treated as disregarded entities |\n| Single-member LLC | Usually **Form 1040 + Schedule C** | **April 15** | Unless taxed as a corporation |\n| Partnership | **Form 1065** | **March 15** | Schedule K-1s go to partners |\n| Multi-member LLC | Usually **Form 1065** | **March 15** | Unless taxed as a corporation |\n| S corporation | **Form 1120-S** | **March 15** | Schedule K-1s go to shareholders |\n| C corporation | **Form 1120** | **April 15** | More generally: 15th day of the 4th month after year-end |\n\n## Estimated Tax Deadlines\n\nFor many small businesses, estimated tax payments are generally due:\n\n- **April 15**\n- **June 15**\n- **September 15**\n- **January 15** of the following year\n\nIf any due date falls on a **Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday**, the deadline moves to the **next business day**.\n\n## Important Reminder\n\n- An **extension gives more time to file**\n- It **does not give more time to pay**\n\n## IRS Sources\n\n- **Filing and paying your business taxes**  \n  https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/filing-and-paying-your-business-taxes\n\n- **IRS Small Businesses and Self-Employed Tax Center**  \n  https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed\n\n- **Publication 334, Tax Guide for Small Business**  \n  https://www.irs.gov/publications/p334\n\nIf you want, I can also make this into a **2026 federal tax calendar with the actual shifted dates** for weekends/holidays."
  },
